
Phase 4 HTTP Service:
====================

This phase contains the deterministic engine plus a prototype HTTP wrapper.
The service accepts a JSON document with `POST /manifest` and returns the
resulting JSON payload. A `GET /healthz` endpoint is also exposed for probes.


Local engine run:
====================

Build and run the file-based engine:

    make -C src/phase-4 clean compile run

Diff the generated output against the golden case:

    make -C src/phase-4 clean compile diff


Package the HTTP service:
====================

Build the Linux Docker image from the repository root:

    docker build -t mademanifest-phase-4:latest src/phase-4

Run it locally:

    docker run --rm -p 8080:8080 mademanifest-phase-4:latest

Test it with the golden input:

    src/phase-4/scripts/request_cloud_service.sh \
        http://localhost:8080/manifest \
        src/phase-4/out/cloud-service-output.json


Install on Kubernetes:
====================

1. Push the image to a registry your cluster can pull from:

       docker tag mademanifest-phase-4:latest registry.example.com/mademanifest/phase-4:latest
       docker push registry.example.com/mademanifest/phase-4:latest

2. Update the image reference in:

       src/phase-4/deploy/kubernetes/deployment.yaml

3. Apply the prototype manifests:

       kubectl apply -f src/phase-4/deploy/kubernetes/configmap.yaml
       kubectl apply -f src/phase-4/deploy/kubernetes/deployment.yaml
       kubectl apply -f src/phase-4/deploy/kubernetes/service.yaml

   Or apply them as one rendered bundle:

       kubectl kustomize src/phase-4/deploy/kubernetes | kubectl apply -f -

4. Wait for the pod to become ready:

       kubectl rollout status deployment/mademanifest

5. Access the service:

       kubectl port-forward service/mademanifest 8080:80

6. Send the golden request through the cluster endpoint:

       src/phase-4/scripts/request_cloud_service.sh \
           http://localhost:8080/manifest \
           src/phase-4/out/cloud-service-output.json


Linux image libraries:
====================

The Linux image installs the Swiss Ephemeris runtime pieces in the standard
locations expected by the Go binary:

- shared library: `/usr/local/lib/libswe.so`
- ephemeris data files: `/usr/local/share/swisseph`
- canon files: `/app/canon`

The container also sets:

- `SE_EPHE_PATH=/usr/local/share/swisseph`
- `CANON_DIRECTORY=/app/canon`

This is the correct layout for a Linux Docker image. The one important fix was
to avoid `make install` in the builder stage because the patched Swiss
Ephemeris install target still shells out through `sudo`. The Dockerfile now
copies the library and headers into `/usr/local` directly during the build.


